Now I can see the failing test `normalizesDiscordantTags`. Let me understand what this test does:

The test is:
```java
@Test public void normalizesDiscordantTags() {
    Parser parser = Parser.xmlParser().settings(ParseSettings.htmlDefault);
    Document document = Jsoup.parse("<div>test</DIV><p></p>", "", parser);
    assertEquals("<div>\n test\n</div>\n<p></p>", document.html());
    // was failing -> toString() = "<div>\n test\n <p></p>\n</div>"
}
```

The issue is that when parsing `<div>test</DIV><p></p>` (where the closing tag `</DIV>` has different case than the opening `<div>`), the parser was incorrectly treating it as a single div element containing a p element, instead of properly closing the div and creating separate elements.

Looking at the `popStackToClose` method in `XmlTreeBuilder.java`, I can see the issue. The method looks for the first occurrence of a tag name when popping the stack, but it's case-sensitive. However, when `ParseSettings.htmlDefault` is used, the tag names should be normalized for comparison, but the current implementation doesn't normalize the tag name comparison.

Let me look more closely at the `popStackToClose` method:

```java
private void popStackToClose(Token.EndTag endTag) {
    String elName = endTag.name();
    Element firstFound = null;

    for (int pos = stack.size() -1; pos >= 0; pos--) {
        Element next = stack.get(pos);
        if (next.nodeName().equals(elName)) {  // This is case-sensitive comparison
            firstFound = next;
            break;
        }
    }
    if (firstFound == null)
        return; // not found, skip

    for (int pos = stack.size() -1; pos >= 0; pos--) {
        Element next = stack.get(pos);
        stack.remove(pos);
        if (next == firstFound)
            break;
    }
}
```

The problem is that when using `ParseSettings.htmlDefault`, the tag names should be compared case-insensitively. Let me check how the HtmlTreeBuilder handles this. The issue is that the comparison `next.nodeName().equals(elName)` is case-sensitive, but it should respect the parse settings.

Let me check how the settings.normalizeTag method works by looking at the implementation:

The issue is that the `popStackToClose` method should normalize the tag names when comparing if the parse settings require it. The method should use the same approach as the rest of the parser does with the settings.

